    <abstract id="aspace_93785abc749eeada1f29683a90be1a1a">These seventeen interviews of longshoremen document their experiences working on waterfronts in New York, New Jersey, and London during the middle of the twentieth century. Subjects discussed include entry into the occupation, working conditions, characteristics of different cargoes, labor relations, relationship between rank and file union members and leadership, ethnic composition on the docks, and Communist Party activity on waterfront. The interviews were taken by Colin J. Davis and used in his 2003 book <title render="italic">Waterfront Revolts: New York and London Dockworkers, 1946-1961</title>.</abstract>
    <langmaterial id="aspace_28d4316c2b8b8a87cc8670bfea254299">Materials are in English.</langmaterial>
